substrate_voxel_check:
  description: "Run the geometric voxel test on every PR that touches substrate.py or the routing test itself — catches collisions before merge."
  match:
    include:
      - "src/vitamins/substrate.py"
      - "tests/test_substrate_routing.py"
  review:
    strategy: all_changed_files
    instructions: |
      A change to substrate.py (routing topology) or test_substrate_routing.py
      (the voxel gate itself) must be validated by running the voxel test
      from the repo root:

          .deepwork/jobs/printable_pcb/scripts/run_voxel_check.sh

      ## What to check

      1. The script's exit code is 0 and stdout reads
         "PASS — all voxel checks green".
      2. If it FAILS, the assertion lines name the colliding (signal pair,
         x, y). Each collision is one of the seven failure modes documented
         in `.deepwork/jobs/printable_pcb/job.yml` under "Known failure
         modes":
           - trunk-through-foreign-pin
           - same-layer-parallel
           - via-in-pocket
           - edge-escape-impossible
           - L2-channel-inside-pocket (board contact)
           - bus-return-blocked-by-power-corridor-stubs
           - sub-printable wall thickness (channels and pin rows < 0.6 mm
             apart in CAD print as one merged void)

      The same test file also enforces an angle-alignment invariant:
      every routed WireSegment must run at a multiple of 45°
      (0°/±45°/±90°/±135°). Arbitrary slopes (e.g. atan2(b, a) for
      unequal-leg L-bends) are forbidden because they don't match the
      printable-design intent. The chamfer post-process in
      `voxel_suggester.apply_chamfers` preserves the invariant by
      construction — verify the new test
      `test_every_segment_is_45_or_90` passes.

      ## Output Format

      - PASS: voxel test green AND angle test green; list the
        substrate classes covered (Tier1Substrate, Tier2Substrate,
        Tier2SubstrateBundled).
      - FAIL (collision): paste the assertion lines verbatim and
        identify which of the seven known failure modes each
        collision falls under.
      - FAIL (angle): name the segment (path, layer, endpoints, angle)
        that violates the 45°-multiple invariant.
